  title="Spiral & Vertical Conveyors: Continuous Elevation Change Systems"
  description="Complete guide to spiral and vertical conveyors: spiral up/down, continuous vs indexed, VRC comparison. Throughput, footprint, and selection for packaging and distribution."
  canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/conveyor-types/spiral-conveyors/"
  schema={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, articleSchema]}
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="bg-surface border-b border-border" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-3">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-ink-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Spiral Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Spiral & Vertical Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Spiral & Vertical Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A spiral conveyor moves products vertically between elevation levels using a helical path that wraps around a central column in a compact footprint. Spiral conveyors handle elevation changes of 3 to 50+ feet with continuous product flow — products enter and exit simultaneously without batch cycling. They serve <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging lines</a>, distribution centers, and food processing facilities where floor space is limited and throughput demands rule out batch-lifting alternatives like <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">vertical reciprocating conveyors (VRCs)</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How Spirals Work -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">How They Work</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How Spiral Conveyors <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>A spiral conveyor wraps a conveying surface — typically a plastic modular belt, slat chain, or wire mesh belt — around a central drum or column in a continuous helix. The belt rides on a support structure that spirals upward (or downward) at a constant pitch angle. A single motor drives the belt through the entire spiral path. Products placed on the belt at the bottom travel upward through the helix and discharge at the top (or vice versa for down-spirals).</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Friction-Drive Spirals</h3>
        <p>Most spiral conveyors use a friction-drive design where the belt wraps around a central rotating drum. The drum surface has a high-friction coating or surface texture. As the drum rotates, friction between the drum and the belt inner edge drives the belt through the spiral. No sprockets, chains, or edge drives are needed. Ryson International and AmbaFlex are the two dominant friction-drive spiral conveyor manufacturers globally.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Ryson and AmbaFlex market positioning as dominant spiral manufacturers -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Chain-Drive Spirals</h3>
        <p>Some spiral conveyors use chain or gear drives to positively move the belt or slat surface through the spiral. Chain-driven spirals handle heavier loads and maintain more precise speed control than friction-drive units. They cost more and require more maintenance (chain lubrication, tension adjustment). Nercon and Garvey Corporation offer chain-driven spiral solutions for heavy-duty packaging applications.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Spiral Geometry</h3>
        <p>Key spiral dimensions: outside diameter (typically 4-10 feet), belt width (6-36 inches), number of tiers (spiral wraps, typically 2-20), elevation change per tier (6-18 inches), and total elevation change (sum of all tier heights). The pitch angle (incline) is typically 5-12 degrees — gentle enough to prevent product sliding but steep enough to gain elevation efficiently. Tighter spirals (smaller diameter) save floor space but increase belt wear and limit belt width.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Spiral Up and Down -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="updown-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Up & Down</div>
      <h2 id="updown-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Spiral Up vs. <span class="text-accent">Spiral Down</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Spiral Up Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Spiral up conveyors lift products from a lower elevation to a higher one. Common applications: lifting cases from a ground-level packaging line to an overhead conveyor system, lifting products from production level to mezzanine-level palletizing, and lifting finished goods from packaging to an elevated shipping conveyor. Spiral up conveyors need more drive power than spiral down because they work against gravity plus friction.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Spiral Down Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Spiral down conveyors lower products from a higher elevation to a lower one. The most common application: lowering products from an overhead conveyor or mezzanine to ground-level shipping. Spiral down conveyors in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food processing</a> lower hot products through cooling zones — the spiral path provides extended dwell time in cooled or ambient air. Bakery lines use cooling spirals to cool bread, baked goods, and confections over 30-60 minutes of spiral travel.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Dual Spirals</h3>
        <p>Dual spiral conveyors stack an up-spiral and a down-spiral concentrically (one inside the other) or side by side. This provides both elevation change and return path in a single footprint. Dual spirals serve applications where products must go up to a process level and return down to the original level — for example, lifting products through an overhead treatment zone (UV curing, cooling, drying) and returning them to the packaging line.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Continuous vs Indexed -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="mode-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Operating Modes</div>
      <h2 id="mode-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Continuous vs. <span class="text-accent">Indexed</span> Operation
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Continuous Flow</h3>
        <p>Continuous-flow spirals run at constant speed with products entering and exiting simultaneously. Belt speed typically ranges from 30 to 200 FPM. Throughput depends on belt speed and product spacing: at 100 FPM with 18-inch product spacing, a continuous spiral delivers 67 products per minute. Continuous spirals suit high-throughput operations where products flow without interruption from upstream <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation systems</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Indexed (Mass Flow) Operation</h3>
        <p>Indexed spirals stop and start to fill the entire spiral with products before advancing the belt. The spiral fills completely during the stop period, then indexes forward to discharge the products. This mode maximizes the number of products in the spiral at any time, providing maximum cooling/holding time per product. Indexed spirals serve food cooling and freezing applications where dwell time matters more than throughput rate.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Hybrid Operation</h3>
        <p>Some spiral systems vary belt speed dynamically to balance throughput and dwell time. Variable-speed drives adjust the spiral speed based on upstream production rate and downstream demand. During high production, the spiral runs faster. During slow periods, the spiral slows to provide more dwell time (cooling, drying) per product. This is common in bakery spiral coolers where production rate varies between product changeovers.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Spiral vs VRC Comparison -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="comparison-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
