              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Continuous</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Batch (stop-start)</td>
              <td class="py-3">Continuous</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Throughput</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">30-200 PPM</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">4-15 cycles/min</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">30-200 PPM</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Elevation Change</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">3-50+ ft</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">3-40 ft</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">3-20 ft</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Floor Space</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Moderate (4-10 ft dia)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Small (shaft footprint)</td>
              <td class="py-3">Large (long incline run)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Max Load/Unit</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">150 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">6,000 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">100 lbs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Best For</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">High-throughput cases/cartons</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Heavy loads, low throughput</td>
              <td class="py-3">Low elevation, long run OK</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Relative Cost</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">See our <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">VRC guide</a> for detailed vertical reciprocating conveyor coverage. See <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cost guide</a> for pricing factors.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Spiral Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Packaging line elevation changes:</strong> Spiral conveyors lift finished cases, cartons, and totes from ground-level packaging to mezzanine-level palletizing or overhead <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation systems</a>. The compact footprint saves floor space compared to long incline conveyors. Ryson spirals are the most common in packaging line applications, offered in widths from 6 to 30 inches.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Food cooling and freezing:</strong> Spiral conveyors in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food processing</a> carry products through cooling or freezing chambers. The spiral path provides 30-120 minutes of dwell time within a compact freezer footprint. Bakery products, pizzas, prepared meals, and meat products ride through spiral freezers at -30 to -40&deg;F. GEA, JBT (FoodTech), and Linde supply spiral freezer systems with integrated spiral conveyors in stainless steel and food-grade plastic belt construction.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: GEA, JBT, Linde current spiral freezer offerings -->

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Distribution center level changes:</strong> Spiral conveyors move totes, cartons, and shipping containers between floors in multi-level distribution centers and fulfillment centers. The continuous flow handles the high throughput of e-commerce operations where batch-lifting VRCs create bottlenecks. AmbaFlex supplies spirals optimized for distribution center applications with wide belts handling multiple products per tier.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Accumulation in vertical space:</strong> Spiral conveyors double as vertical <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation buffers</a>. The spiral path provides 50-200 feet of conveyor length within a small floor footprint. Slowing or stopping the spiral accumulates products throughout the helix. This is more floor-space-efficient than long horizontal accumulation lanes for applications where vertical space is available.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Proofing and drying:</strong> Spirals carry bakery dough through temperature and humidity-controlled proofing chambers. The extended spiral path provides the 30-90 minute dwell time needed for dough rising. Similarly, spirals carry coated, washed, or printed products through drying zones where extended air exposure removes moisture. The spiral geometry maximizes dwell time per cubic foot of chamber volume.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Clean room and pharmaceutical:</strong> Spiral conveyors in enclosed housings move products between clean room levels or between production and packaging areas at different elevations. Stainless steel construction and smooth surfaces meet pharmaceutical and clean room standards. The enclosed spiral prevents contamination during vertical transport.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Selection Guide -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Select a <span class="text-accent">Spiral Conveyor</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Elevation change and available floor space set the diameter and tier count.</strong> Divide the total elevation change by the elevation per tier (typically 6-18 inches) to get the number of tiers. More tiers mean a taller spiral. A larger diameter allows more elevation per tier (steeper pitch) and more belt area but consumes more floor space.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Product dimensions and weight determine belt width and type.</strong> The product must fit within the belt width with clearance on both sides. Product weight must not exceed the belt and drive capacity per linear foot. Typical spiral belts handle 25-50 lbs per linear foot. Heavy products (over 75 lbs each) may require chain-driven spirals or <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">VRC alternatives</a>.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Throughput determines belt speed and product spacing.</strong> Calculate products per minute. Divide belt speed (FPM) by product pitch (product length + gap). Ensure the calculation accounts for infeed and discharge conveyor speeds. <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Transfer conveyors</a> at the spiral infeed and discharge must match the spiral belt speed for smooth product transition.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Environment defines materials and belt type.</strong> Standard packaging: steel frame, plastic modular belt. Washdown food: stainless steel frame, open-mesh belt for drainage. Freezer: stainless steel with low-temperature belt material rated for -40&deg;F. High-temperature: heat-resistant belt and lubrication for oven and drying applications.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Maintenance accessibility matters.</strong> Spiral interiors are difficult to access. Select spirals with removable covers, hinged sections, or walk-in designs for belt cleaning, adjustment, and replacement. Belt replacement on a 20-tier spiral is a significant maintenance event — design for accessibility from the start.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a spiral conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>A spiral conveyor moves products vertically using a helical belt path around a central column. Elevation changes from 3 to 50+ feet with continuous flow — products enter and exit simultaneously. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor type guide</a> for all vertical transport options.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Spiral conveyor vs VRC — which should I choose?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Spiral for high-throughput continuous flow of cases and cartons (under 150 lbs each). <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">VRC</a> for heavier loads (up to 6,000 lbs), lower throughput, and smaller footprint. Spirals cost more but eliminate batch-cycling delays. VRCs handle pallets and heavy loads that spirals cannot.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How much does a spiral conveyor cost?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Spiral conveyors are $$$$-level capital investments. Cost depends on elevation, belt width, tier count, environment (washdown, freezer), and construction material. They justify cost through continuous throughput and small footprint. See our <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for detailed factors.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ink-light" aria-labelledby="related-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent-bright mb-4">Related Pages</div>
      <h2 id="related-heading" class="font-display text-3xl font-800 text-white tracking-wide mb-8">Continue <span class="text-accent-bright">Researching</span></h2>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
        <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] hover:bg-white/[0.06] hover:border-accent/40 transition-all group">
          <div class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white group-hover:text-accent-bright transition-colors mb-1">VRC Systems</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-white/60">Batch-lift vertical alternative</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] hover:bg-white/[0.06] hover:border-accent/40 transition-all group">
          <div class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white group-hover:text-accent-bright transition-colors mb-1">Accumulation</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-white/60">Buffer before spiral infeed</p>
